in in @byted-service/fetch, actually can be used without any operation.\n\n```ts\nimport { fetch } from '@byted-service/fetch';\nimport { handle } from '@byted-service/fetch-protocol-http';\n\nfetch.register('http', handle);\nfetch.register('https', handle);\n\n(async () => {\n    const resp = await fetch('http://www.domain.com/xxx');\n\n    console.log(await resp.text());\n})();\n```\n\n## API\n\n### fetch(url[, options])\n\nThe parameters of `@byted-service/fetch` have been extended. Generally, It is set by framework, and user unaware.\n\n<details>\n  <summary>History</summary>\n\n-   `v1.3.0`: Support `options.enableHttpMesh`. Support `http://` protocol to work with `Mesh`.\n\n</details>\n\n-   `url`: request url.\n-   `options`:\n    -   `enableHttpMesh`: Whether to send request through `http egress mesh`, the default value is `false`. Different from `enableMesh`, this parameter is only applicable to `http://` protocol, if you need `http://` protocol to work with `mesh`, you can enable this.\n\n## HTTP Egress Mesh\n\nFor historical reasons:\n\n1. `options.enableMesh` existed before `Mesh` supported the `http://` protocol and defaulted to `true`.\n2. `Mesh`'s `http://` protocol does not support `ip:port` and does not work for all `http://` protocol use cases.\n\nTherefore, it is impossible to pass all `http://` protocol traffic to `Mesh` by default, and it is impossible to change the default value of `options.enableMesh` to `false`, so it can only to add the `options.enableHttpMesh` to decide whether should `http://` protocol work with `Mesh`.\n\n**For people who is determined to allow the `http://` protocol to work with `Mesh`, you can set `options.enableHttpMesh = true`.**\n","time":{"1.1.2-beta.0":"2022-06-23T10:08:08.955Z","1.2.0":"2022-07-12T10:45:25.437Z","1.3.0":"2022-08-19T06:22:31.382Z","1.3.1":"2022-11-21T04:24:09.495Z","1.3.3":"2023-08-21T12:43:43.031Z","1.3.4":"2024-07-26T03:57:56.474Z","1.1.0":"2022-03-22T05:48:12.225Z","1.1.2":"2022-06-24T03:53:19.3